Nobody answers my question yet but I&#39;m still advancing in my project, as I mentioned before, I modified the code to use more the .kv file, now I have the main screen and the secondary screens.

The project is about a yearbook with 12 months and every month with 30 days, the idea is that the user has a global vision of the follow up of his activity for a year in a single view.

In the screen &quot;main&quot;, each button of the calendar represents a day (365 buttons) and each button directs towards another screen (1, 2, 3, ..., 365) where there are four &quot;CheckBox&quot; that show the activities are identified with the letters (R, F, C, T), which can be selected individually or in group in any order and any quantity, for example: R, RC, RFT, RFCT. 

We also have three buttons (Accept, Clean, Return); with &quot;Accept&quot; I send internally the &quot;CheckBox&quot; selected to the screen &quot;main&quot; and then with the button &quot;Return&quot; I return to &quot;main&quot; and I can see the data of my selection made; with the button &quot;Clean&quot; I can delete the selection made previously and when I press the button &quot;Back&quot;, I would find that day without any data, completely clean, and if I want I can enter again and make a different selection.

What is missing is that the selection made and that I already have in the main screen or in &quot;main&quot;, I can save it in a backup so that when I close the application the data will not be erased, so that when I open it again, they will be there on each of the days that I have selected during the time of use of the application.

On the other hand, it is missing that in the days the selected options the letters have the color according to each selection of the checkboxes.

Next I share the codes .py and .kv that I have realized and that I already commented to them, in order that you can verify it in your PC&#39;s in case somebody wants to find a possible solution; I must indicate that the code next, is in a minimum expression of only one month (January) and only four days (1, 2, 3, 4), since all the complete year is a lot of code to publish directly here in this WebSite.

Before I show you the minimized code, I leave you images of what it looks like when you have the whole year to get an idea of the project:

