This happens because your fields in the HTML document are named incorrectly.

Currently:

`teacher[firstname]`

but rather should be (more or less):

`teacher_teacher[firstname]`

Use a `FormFactoryInterface` to created a named form instead:

    public function yourAction(Request $request, FormFactoryInterface $forms)
    {
        $form = $this-&gt;forms-&gt;createNamed(&#39;&#39;, TeacherType::class);
        $form-&gt;handleRequest($request);

        if ($form-&gt;isSubmitted() &amp;&amp; !$form-&gt;isValid()) {
            return new JsonResponse([
                &#39;code&#39; =&gt; &#39;400&#39;,
                &#39;data&#39; =&gt; $this-&gt;getErrorMessages($form),
            ]);
        }

        return new JsonResponse([&#39;code&#39; =&gt; 200]);
    }

When you create a form without a name (eg. `$this-&gt;createForm(TeacherType::class)`) a name is autogenerated for you: the name of the form without `Form` and `Type` words in the end, thus the need to have the `teacher_` part before the field&#39;s name.

