answers.body_markdown:
You have not initialised `input_ptr` so the code has undefined behaviour. You might have passed an invalid buffer address to `getline`. You should also initialise `input_length`, so 

    char *input_ptr = NULL;
    size_t input_length = 0;
    
The function [`getline()`](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man3/getline.3.html) expects either a pointer to memory you allocated yourself, or `NULL` to indicate that the function should allocate memory.

&gt; If `*lineptr` is set to `NULL` and `*n` is set `0` before the call, then `getline()` will allocate a buffer for storing the line. This buffer should be freed by the user program even if `getline()` failed.

Note, you should not increment a pointer which you intend to free later.

